join Alice (half) center
[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/c5s5/Alice_approaches_looking_curious.mp3" volume="0.0" bus="Voice"]
Alice approaches, looking curious.
if {selected_character} == "celestine":
	Alice: Celestine, I heard you helped solve four major cases this year.
	Alice: The exam theft, the missing fund, the broken sculpture, and the journal incident.
	Alice: How did you do it? What's your secret?
	Celestine: No secret. Just observation, evidence, and trying to understand people.
	Celestine: Every mystery is really about understanding why people make the choices they do.
	Alice: So you're like... a detective psychologist?
	Celestine: Maybe. Or maybe just someone trying to help.
	Alice: Could you teach me? How to observe like you do?
	[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/c5s5/The_Protagonist_considers_B_C_taught_you_through_experience_not_lectures.mp3" volume="0.0" bus="Voice"]
	Celestine considers. B.C. taught her through experience, not lectures.
	Celestine: I can't teach you directly. But I can suggest something.
	Celestine: Pay attention. Really look at what's around you. Listen when people speak.
	Celestine: Try to understand motivations, not just actions.
	Celestine: And when you see someone struggling, ask yourself\: What are they really afraid of? What do they really need?
	Alice: That's... simpler than I expected. But harder to actually do.
	Celestine: Exactly. The best lessons are like that.
	Alice: Thanks, Celestine. I'll try.
	leave Alice
	leave Mark
	[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/c5s5/The_Protagonist_stands_alone_for_a_moment_watching_students_move_through_the_courtyard.mp3" volume="0.0" bus="Voice"]
